According to the graph above, the data has both upward trend and seasonality. Also, the Box-Cox transformation is necessary for this dataset since the curve is a little bit convave up, and it shows increasing variantion as the level of the series increases. Thus, it needs the Box-Cox transformation to stabilize the variance.

  1. In this section you will apply the time-series cross validation method to train and test various models.
k <- 160 # minimum data length for fitting a model
n <- length(data) # Number of data points

p <- 12 ### Period
H <- 12 # Forecast Horiz
defaultW <- getOption("warn") 
options(warn = -1)

st <- tsp(data)[1]+(k-2)/p #  gives the start time in time units,

Aria_mae1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
Aria_mae2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
Aria_RMSE1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
Aria_RMSE2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
Aria_aicc1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,1)
Aria_aicc2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,1)


for(i in 1:(n-k))
{
  
  ### One Month rolling forecasting
  # Expanding Window 
  train_1_arima <- window(data, end=st + i/p)  ## Window Length: k+i
  
  # Sliding Window - keep the training window of fixed length. 
  # The training set always consists of k observations.
  train_2_arima <- window(data, start=st+(i-k+1)/p, end=st+i/p) ## Window Length: k
  
  test_arima <- window(data, start=st + (i+1)/p, end=st + (i+H)/p) ## Window Length: H

  if (i<4) {
  cat(c("*** CV", i,":","len(Expanding Window):",length(train_1_arima), "len(Sliding Window):",length(train_2_arima), "len(Test):",length(test_arima),'\n'  ))
  cat(c("*** TRAIN -  Expanding WIndow:",tsp(train_1_arima)[1],'-',tsp(train_1_arima)[2],'\n'))
  cat(c("*** TRAIN - Sliding WIndow:",tsp(train_2_arima)[1],'-',tsp(train_2_arima)[2],'\n'))
  cat(c("*** TEST:",tsp(test_arima)[1],'-',tsp(test_arima)[2],'\n'))
  cat("*************************** \n \n")
  }
  
  
  fit_1_arima <- Arima(train_1_arima, order=c(1,0,1), seasonal=list(order=c(0,1,2), period=p),
                include.drift=TRUE, lambda=lambda, method="ML")
  fcast_1_arima <- forecast(fit_1_arima, h=H)
  
  
  fit_2_arima <- Arima(train_2_arima, order=c(1,0,1), seasonal=list(order=c(0,1,2), period=p),
                include.drift=TRUE, lambda=lambda, method="ML")
  fcast_2_arima <- forecast(fit_2_arima, h=H)
  
  
  
  Aria_mae1[i,1:length(test_arima)] <- abs(fcast_1_arima[['mean']]-test_arima)
  Aria_mae2[i,1:length(test_arima)] <- abs(fcast_2_arima[['mean']]-test_arima)
  Aria_RMSE1[i,1:length(test_arima)] <- sqrt(mean((fcast_1_arima[['mean']]-test_arima)^2))
  Aria_RMSE2[i,1:length(test_arima)] <- sqrt(mean((fcast_2_arima[['mean']]-test_arima)^2))
  Aria_aicc1[i] <- fit_1_arima$aicc
  Aria_aicc2[i] <- fit_2_arima$aicc
}

defaultW <- getOption("warn") 
options(warn = -1)

st <- tsp(data)[1]+(k-2)/p #  gives the start time in time units,

ETS_mae1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
ETS_mae2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
ETS_rmse1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
ETS_rmse2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,H)
ETS_aicc1 <- matrix(NA,n-k,1)
ETS_aicc2 <- matrix(NA,n-k,1)


for(i in 1:(n-k))
{
  
  
  ### One Month rolling forecasting
  # Expanding Window 
  train_1_ets <- window(data, end=st + i/p)  ## Window Length: k+i
  
  # Sliding Window - keep the training window of fixed length. 
  # The training set always consists of k observations.
  train_2_ets <- window(data, start=st+(i-k+1)/p, end=st+i/p) ## Window Length: k
  
  test_ets <- window(data, start=st + (i+1)/p, end=st + (i+H)/p) ## Window Length: H

  if (i<4) {
  cat(c("*** CV", i,":","len(Expanding Window):",length(train_1_ets), "len(Sliding Window):",length(train_2_ets), "len(Test):",length(test_ets),'\n'  ))
  cat(c("*** TRAIN -  Expanding WIndow:",tsp(train_1_ets)[1],'-',tsp(train_1_ets)[2],'\n'))
  cat(c("*** TRAIN - Sliding WIndow:",tsp(train_2_ets)[1],'-',tsp(train_2_ets)[2],'\n'))
  cat(c("*** TEST:",tsp(test_ets)[1],'-',tsp(test_ets)[2],'\n'))
  cat("*************************** \n \n")
  }
  
  fit_1_ets <- ets(train_1_ets, model = "MAM")
  fcast_1_ets <- forecast(fit_1_ets, h=12)
  
  fit_2_ets <- ets(train_2_ets, model = "MAM")
  fcast_2_ets <- forecast(fit_2_ets, h=12)
  
  ETS_mae1[i,1:length(test_ets)] <- abs(fcast_1_ets[['mean']]-test_ets)
  ETS_mae2[i,1:length(test_ets)] <- abs(fcast_2_ets[['mean']]-test_ets)
  ETS_rmse1[i,1:length(test_ets)] <- sqrt(mean((fcast_1_ets[['mean']]-test_ets)^2))
  ETS_rmse2[i,1:length(test_ets)] <- sqrt(mean((fcast_2_ets[['mean']]-test_ets)^2))
  ETS_aicc1[i] <- fit_1_ets$aicc
  ETS_aicc2[i] <- fit_2_ets$aicc
}

plot(1:12, colMeans(Aria_mae1,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=1,xlab="horizon value", ylab="MAE value",ylim=c(0,50))
lines(1:12, colMeans(Aria_mae2,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=2)
lines(1:12, colMeans(ETS_mae1,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=3)
lines(1:12, colMeans(ETS_mae2,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=4)
legend("topleft",legend=c("ARIMA - Expanding Window","ARIMA - Sliding Window", "ETS - Expanding Window","ETS - Sliding Window"),col=1:4,lty=1)

From the MAE graph, we can see that Arima sliding window has the lowest error and ETS expanding windwo has the highest error. So from the MAE standing of view, the Arima sliding model perform the best.

plot(1:12, colMeans(Aria_RMSE1,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=1,xlab="horizon", ylab="RMSE value",ylim=c(28,33))
lines(1:12, colMeans(Aria_RMSE2,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=2)
lines(1:12, colMeans(ETS_rmse1,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=3)
lines(1:12, colMeans(ETS_rmse2,na.rm=TRUE), type="l",col=4)
legend("topleft",legend=c("ARIMA - Expanding Window","ARIMA - Sliding Window", "ETS - Expanding Window","ETS - Sliding Window"),col=1:4,lty=1)

From the rmse graph, we can see that the Arima models(especially the sliding model) have lower RMSE than ETS model. This means that Arima sliding model preforms the best.

plot(1:80, Aria_aicc1, type="l",col=1,xlab="Iterations",ylim=c(-1000,3000))
lines(1:80, Aria_aicc2, type="l",col=2)
lines(1:80, ETS_aicc1, type="l",col=3)
lines(1:80, ETS_aicc2, type="l",col=4)
legend("topleft",legend=c("ARIMA - Expanding Window","ARIMA - Sliding Window", "ETS - Expanding Window","ETS - Sliding Window"),col=1:4,lty=1)

AICc between two different models can not be compared since they should be in different scales. But, from the graph, we can tell that the aicc for Arima model is lower than aicc for ETS model. This means that Arima model perform better.

plot(1:80, Aria_aicc1, type="l",col=1,xlab="Iterations",ylim=c(-10,100))
lines(1:80, Aria_aicc2, type="l",col=2)
legend("topleft",legend=c("ARIMA - Expanding Window","ARIMA - Sliding Window"),col=1:4,lty=1)

And from the graph above, we can see that the aicc of Arima sliding model is lower than that of Arima expanding model. This means that Arima sliding model perform better.

  1. What are the disadvantages of the above methods? What would be a better approach to estimate the models? Hint: How were the SARIMA and exponential time series models determined in question 3?

  1. We have to use the data after the box-cox transformation. Since the auto-arima model gives us c(1,0,1), c(0,1,2) and we directly apply that in both models, we use the un-transformed data above. We should use fit1_wboxcox, which has different p,d,q as the previous one.

  2. The Scale-dependent errors, such as ME, MPE, RMSE, are based on a set scale, which cannot be used to make comparisons that are on a different scale.

  3. AICc is useful for selecting between models in the same class. However, it cannot be used to compare between ETS and ARIMA models because they are in different model classes, and the likelihood is computed in different ways.

In terms of a better approach to estimate the models, we can also calculate the computational power for both models. Based on the models I run, I found that although arima model has lower Scale-dependent errors, it took more time to run than the ets model.
